  <span id="freeText11879452067583331305" style="display:none">Firmin is a rat that, as a result of a steady diet of books, has developed the capacity to read and to think like a human being. This makes him unique among his fellow rats and leads to a life of isolation. Firmin continuously struggles to find someone to attach himself to but all of his interactions with humans fail to lead to anything like a meaningful friendship. Overall, this is a book about loneliness, especially as a result of being unique, and about decay and loss, as the neighborhood where Firmin lives gets destroyed in order to make room for something new (property development at its best). While I do like the overall theme, I found Firmin's character totally despicable and I also did not jam with the ostentatiously patronizing way in which the book was written. I do understand that this is part of Firmin's character as a lonely and rejected rat, but this did not make reading his exploits any fun. </span>
