  <span id="freeText7927423173668187988" style="display:none">This is a masterpiece that many people have never heard of. Firmin is a rat living in a Boston bookstore. He eventually learns to read. The author, the late Sam Savage, has Firmin take the reader on a literary tour-de-force. Firmin is better read than most people I know, including me.<br /><br />Although Firmin is a rat, I quickly identified with him. Not the tail and yellow teeth, but his intelligence, his philosophy of life, his taste as a reader, and his empathy for the humans he lives with. His attempts to convince humans that he is both harmless and a philosopher are both comical and sad.<br /><br />This is a rat, that if I saw him, I think I would try to make friends with. Any creature who loves James Joyce and Ford Maddox Ford can be a friend of mine. Plus, he's a fan of Ginger Rogers and Fred Astaire. You cannot go wrong with that.<br /><br />I highly recommend this book.<br /></span>
