<span id="freeTextContainer17217245546532880298">A letter I wrote to Sam Savage but couldn&apos;t figure out where to send it. <br/>To Sam Savage,<br/>I was walking through the aisles of my local library branch with no idea of what book I wanted to read. I bided my time because it was the afternoon and that meant that my house was hot and humid and the library was not. I skimmed the aisles of stacks of rows of books and plucked them one by one off the shelves. I took in title upon title and tried to guess what a cover art had to do with the descriptions. You</span>
  <span id="freeText17217245546532880298" style="display:none">A letter I wrote to Sam Savage but couldn't figure out where to send it. <br />To Sam Savage,<br />I was walking through the aisles of my local library branch with no idea of what book I wanted to read. I bided my time because it was the afternoon and that meant that my house was hot and humid and the library was not. I skimmed the aisles of stacks of rows of books and plucked them one by one off the shelves. I took in title upon title and tried to guess what a cover art had to do with the descriptions. You can imagine what a long task this was, but it is summer and a girl like me needed a hidden book to praise. I felt the pressure to get going as my sister came to stand at my side and I pulled out a book to which I had never reacted so unexpectedly before. That book was yours; that book was Firmin.<br />Upon feeling the jagged edges in it's design and seeing the cover, I gasped, thinking the book was falling apart in my hands. I took a step back and took a better look at it and my sister and I laughed and ignored the signs to be quiet. I read the back, read the front, and tucked the book into the crook of my arm.<br />I checked the books out, went home, and Firmin was the one I carried in my bag the next day to work. I cracked it open, it amazes me how many books at my library are never used and abused. Have all of the adults in my town grown out of reading? I began the book not knowing what to expect. I closed the book everyday not knowing what to anticipate in the next paragraph. I finished your book in a few short days and realized that it would weigh heavily on my mind if I didn't find a way to write to you and tell you this: Thank you for writing this book.<br />You see, I don't often find books I enjoy, I don't often find authors with a thought process as grand as yours. You taught me so much and Firmin is a great book about those who love books, those who love those people who love books, those who write them, those who sell them! All in a condensed black book of 164 pages.<br />It brings a tear to my eye when I think about it because books and the worlds they contain can be insignificant in it's binding- but sometimes, a book can mean the world to somebody. Books were Firmin's world and if it weren't for his discovery of them, he would have been just another rat scurrying in an alleyway. There's all this meaning I took from his rodent life! You took a cranny in a bookshop, a lonely rat nest, a dust bowl, and gave it life. It has flourished in this book and I am glad I picked it up.<br />Can I tell you that one of my favorite aspects of your book was when you would describe the entirety of other books? Can I tell you that I think it is interesting the realness that came along with this book- your research- the life you have lived? I don't think there could be a more perfect union.<br />I just wanted you to know how I felt about this book. I will be a vagrant and place this book with the cover facing out so that others will see it and know that I want them to read it. I want this book to have finger stains, and a cracked spine. I want this book to learn the grooves on the hands of others and I want others to read the life of Firmin. Contrary to what Firmin said about his piano during the wrecking of his home: "I imagined it giving forth a last tiny sound of its own, and no one would hear it." I want all my friends to hear about this.<br /></span>
