  <span id="freeText17813243443344245855" style="display:none">This is, without a doubt, one of the most unusual books I've ever read. At first glance, I thought it was a childrens book. It's definitely NOT a childrens book. It's an adult novel about...a rat. This rat, Firmin, identifies with humans more than other rats. This is due to the fact that as a baby, and as the runt of the litter, he had to turn to eating books because he couldn't compete with his bigger, greedier brothers and sisters for food. Ingesting these books caused him to learn how to read. He became a voracious reader even after he lost his taste for books. OK, you say, why would I want to read a book about a rat? Well, there's so much more to this book. It's laugh-out-loud funny. It's clever. It's weird. There are lots of references to books that will make you say, "Oh yeah, I read that." The characters are memorable. The story is accompanied by little illustrations that aren't even particularly well-done, but they add so much to the story. Most of all, though, there's a pervading sense of deep sadness throughout this book. I know that might seem surprising but this book is full of surprises. It's about the destruction of a formerly glorious part of Boston. It's about the sad sacks of society. It's about the awful plight of rats. Even Fermin, as unusual of a rat as he is, still craps on his best friend, Jerry's, pillow and bites his finger. In the end, he's still a...rat. But you'll never love or feel more sorry for a rat than in this book. The end will not be good for Fermin; you know it, he knows it. But Savage surprises you again and Fermin's story comes full circle.</span>
